                    <msContents>
                        <summary> A treatise on surgery by <persName>Honma Sōken</persName>, also
                            known as Genchō, covering a number of Honma’s surgical practices,
                            including an amputation of a gangrenous leg undertaken in 1857, in
                            katakana-majiri script, with coloured illustrations by an unknown
                            artist. It was privately published by the author in <date>1859</date>,
                            and distributed for sale by Izumiya Kin’emon of Edo and other commercial
                            publishers in Kyoto, Osaka and Nagoya. </summary>

                        <textLang mainLang="ja" source="IANA">Japanese</textLang>

                        <msItem n="1" xml:id="Japanese_20">

                            <author key="person_76237324" source="VIAF">
                                <persName type="original" xml:lang="ja">本間棗軒</persName>
                                <persName type="standard" xml:lang="ja-Latn">Honma Sōken</persName>
                                <note> Honma Sōken (1804-1872) entered Hanaoka Seishū’s school of
                                    surgery in 1827 but left after a short while to spend two months
                                    studying in Nagasaki with Philipp Granz von Siebold (1796-1866),
                                    the doctor at Deshima who was later to achieve fame as a
                                    japanologist. Honma’s view was that Hanaoka Seishū’s surgical
                                    techniques were superior to Siebold’s.</note>
                            </author>

                            <respStmt>
                                <persName type="original" xml:lang="ja">和泉屋金右衛門</persName>
